17
00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:09.600
Okay, so I'm going to talk a little bit about where we are with

18
00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:12.520
pancreatic cancer, which has really been

19
00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:16.360
a really tough challenge, especially in the early detection space.

20
00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:18.600
Here are my disclosures.

21
00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:23.980
So despite having worked on this disease for many years, and some of you in the

22
00:01:24.060 --> 00:01:26.670
audience may also be working on this disease, it's

23
00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:29.320
a little bit heartbreaking to see we're still at a

24
00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:34.060
13% five-year survival, and that was the same rate

25
00:01:34.140 --> 00:01:37.840
that we had last year. And, of course, we

26
00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:41.520
know that there are new therapeutics that are now being deployed for pancreatic

27
00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:43.680
cancer, and we're seeing significant results

28
00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:46.380
when they're applied in the metastatic setting.

29
00:01:47.020 --> 00:01:51.000
However, I think it's going to be a combination of new, more promising

30
00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:54.760
effective therapeutics and down staging of pancreatic cancer that's probably going

31
00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:58.140
to be the magical combination to make advances in this disease.

32
00:01:58.660 --> 00:02:00.620
This is not a disease that's going away.

33
00:02:00.780 --> 00:02:04.620
When I started working on it, it was thought to be a relatively uncommon cancer,

34
00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:08.549
but the incidence has been increasing globally as shown by this

35
00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:10.660
data. And even in the United States,

36
00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:15.460
American Cancer Society facts and figures showing an increase of 1%

37
00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:19.420
incidence per year since the year 2000.

38
00:02:21.140 --> 00:02:24.460
We know some of the risk factors for pancreas cancer, but

39
00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:28.520
I personally find when I go to clinic and see patients with pancreas cancer, only

40
00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:32.540
about 50% of the patients that come in with a de novo pancreas

41
00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:36.400
cancer can we clearly put our finger on with this risk factor, so we

42
00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:40.320
still have some work to do here. We're going to be talking a little bit about the

43
00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:43.989
genetic risk, which conservatively is associated with about

44
00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:47.760
10% of pancreas cancers, but could be as high as 15% to even potentially

45
00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:51.260
20% if you take into account moderate risk genes.

46
00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:56.240
For the risk factors we know about, smoking, obesity, heavy alcohol

47
00:02:56.380 --> 00:02:59.120
use, especially if it's associated with chronic pancreatitis,

48
00:02:59.860 --> 00:03:03.740
diabetes, these are relative risk factors, but

49
00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:06.600
really not more than a twofold known increase.

50
00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:10.800
We do know there's a higher incidence in Blacks, and you can see the data here.

51
00:03:11.250 --> 00:03:14.960
And in general, this has been thought to be a cancer that we see in older

52
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:15.459
people.

53
00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:19.900
But I just want to highlight there has been a concerning

54
00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:23.880
amount of data about a generational shift in cancer incidence, and this is

55
00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:27.540
across about eight to 10 different cancers, but does include

56
00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:28.560
pancreatic cancer.

57
00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:33.500
And we're starting to see this now in the clinics where we're starting to

58
00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:37.410
see patients come in who have pancreatic cancer in their 30s and 40s, where in the

59
00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:41.340
past that was not very common. We don't have

60
00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:45.300
complete insight into this yet, so I think there's some interesting

61
00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:49.140
work that's being done around this with colon cancer, and I know Ludmil Alexandrov

62
00:03:49.180 --> 00:03:52.600
is giving a plenary session at this meeting where he'll

63
00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:56.620
talk about some of his microbiome work that's been pretty compelling.

64
00:03:56.700 --> 00:04:00.120
But this is something we still need to delve in across all the

65
00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:02.400
cancers by which we're seeing this.

66
00:04:04.340 --> 00:04:08.100
And even at this point of having done a lot of work as a

67
00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:12.180
field in pancreatic cancer, these kinds of films are still

68
00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:14.460
not uncommon in the clinic,

69
00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:19.560
where people have locally advanced cancers, where we have limited

70
00:04:19.601 --> 00:04:23.520
surgical options for these patients because of extensive vascular involvement as

71
00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:27.460
shown on the scan on the left, or frankly, metastatic disease, and still half

72
00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:31.180
of patients when they come into the clinic have metastatic disease

73
00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:33.260
at their initial presentation.

74
00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:38.760
So we still do not fully

75
00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:42.700
understand who is at risk for pancreas cancer, what's the level of risk,

76
00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:46.720
and then, of course, what we can do about it, both in terms of early detection and

77
00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:48.880
prevention. And I think this is

78
00:04:49.680 --> 00:04:53.540
the important data point for us to all keep our eye on, and this

79
00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:57.560
is five-year-old SEER data that if you are identified as having a Stage IA

80
00:04:57.620 --> 00:05:00.260
pancreas cancer, which is two centimeters or less,

81
00:05:01.240 --> 00:05:04.340
that the five-year survival rate is 83%.

82
00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:08.320
So we know 83% is a very different number than 13%, and I

83
00:05:08.340 --> 00:05:12.020
would like to make the case that of all the investment we should be making in

84
00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:16.060
pancreas cancer right now, it's probably in early detection.

85
00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:19.540
Now, how do we get

86
00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:23.540
to having effective early detection, understanding risk?

87
00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:27.640
It's for this reason we started an effort

88
00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:29.820
called PRECEDE, and

89
00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:33.440
what we're really seeing is a lot of institutional

90
00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:38.240
or individual efforts around trying to understand early detection, but this is

91
00:05:38.300 --> 00:05:39.840
something that really needed to have

92
00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:44.100
a scale-up to tackle it in the proper way.

93
00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:48.700
So we developed a collaborative research effort, which has now grown

94
00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:52.300
and involves 65 academic centers around the world,

95
00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:56.260
all focused on changing outcomes for pancreas cancer through early detection.

96
00:05:56.300 --> 00:05:59.890
There's another 30 to 40 centers in queue that are getting their regulatory

97
00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:03.700
documents in place. And we set an ambitious

98
00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:06.680
goal to get for a five-year survival rate from 13% to

99
00:06:06.940 --> 00:06:10.280
50% by driving early detection.

100
00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:14.500
And this has grown now to be the largest effort of its kind, and

101
00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:18.640
by using a novel model of data and bio

102
00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:22.580
sample sharing and collaboration, we do think this will help get

103
00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:24.200
us to early detection much more

104
00:06:24.260 --> 00:06:28.100
quickly.This study was set up to try

105
00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:28.860
to answer

106
00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:32.080
and address some of the points made on this slide.

107
00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:36.840
We standardized collection of clinical laboratory and imaging data, as well

108
00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:39.560
as biosamples for a longitudinal study of

109
00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:42.880
individuals at higher risk of pancreas cancer

110
00:06:42.900 --> 00:06:46.500
worldwide. We still don't have proof that screening

111
00:06:46.580 --> 00:06:50.380
saves lives. We can hypothesize it does, and small

112
00:06:50.500 --> 00:06:54.480
studies would suggest that's the case, but we don't have the formal definitive

113
00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:55.420
proof around this.

114
00:06:56.260 --> 00:07:00.040
We need to understand not only the genetic, but also the environmental risks

115
00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:03.980
associated with pancreas cancer, and this study positions us to do

116
00:07:04.020 --> 00:07:07.780
so. Eighty-five percent of heritable pancreas

117
00:07:07.860 --> 00:07:08.340
cancer,

118
00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:12.600
which we call familial pancreas cancer, the genetic cause is unknown.

119
00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:16.020
So we have the potential to address this. I'll talk about that a little bit later.

120
00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:20.100
And then certainly by having this platform, any new

121
00:07:20.200 --> 00:07:21.480
tool upon

122
00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:26.140
which you want to say it improves our ability to detect pancreas cancer

123
00:07:26.240 --> 00:07:30.000
early, this will be a platform which can be effectively

124
00:07:30.020 --> 00:07:30.560
deployed.

125
00:07:32.080 --> 00:07:35.660
And then, not lost on us, if we have a large enough

126
00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:39.670
cohort and have a good early detection test, then we have

127
00:07:39.700 --> 00:07:43.400
the opportunity to do interception and prevention

128
00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:43.990
studies.

129
00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:47.920
So we started this study, and it's really to

130
00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:53.040
try to understand risk and early detection in

131
00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:56.800
anyone who might come in the clinic who is worried about their

132
00:07:56.840 --> 00:08:00.100
pancreatic cancer risk, and I'll show you who I mean by that.

133
00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:03.990
We initially planned a 10,000-patient, 10-year study, but

134
00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:07.440
we've already surpassed that, so now we're going to be enrolling a total of

135
00:08:07.660 --> 00:08:08.840
20,000 patients.

136
00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:14.200
For centers to participate, we want centers to

137
00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:15.860
have some organization and

138
00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:21.000
see at least 50 to 75 high-risk patients a year, have

139
00:08:21.080 --> 00:08:24.490
an organized team in place, infrastructure to collect data and

140
00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:28.280
samples, and agree to share data and samples to join.

141
00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:31.980
Now, who do we follow in this study?

142
00:08:32.060 --> 00:08:35.980
This is a really important part that I think is going to pay off in

143
00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.841
the long term. Cohort one is the cohort that would

144
00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:42.680
be typically followed at centers like yours.

145
00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:46.520
These are people that will have familial pancreas cancer or have mutations

146
00:08:46.700 --> 00:08:49.320
and a family member with pancreas cancer.

147
00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:53.140
And this is already in the NCCN guidelines that these folks should get annual

148
00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:57.260
imaging, which normally would constitute getting an MRI alternating with

149
00:08:57.320 --> 00:08:58.820
an endoscopic ultrasound.

150
00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:02.640
Cohort two is an interesting one. This is one we

151
00:09:02.780 --> 00:09:04.140
started,

152
00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:08.560
and it includes people with ATM, BRCA1 and 2 mutations,

153
00:09:08.660 --> 00:09:12.440
PALB2. People who have two first-degree relatives on one

154
00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:16.240
side, but perhaps not a first-degree relative, and if we have someone who

155
00:09:16.360 --> 00:09:19.200
has a family history of early onset cancer.

156
00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:23.060
And when we started collecting these patients and following

157
00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:26.820
them, it was not in any guidelines that any of

158
00:09:27.240 --> 00:09:29.940
the folks in this cohort should get longitudinal screening.

159
00:09:30.020 --> 00:09:33.860
But since then, there are two guidelines that have put forth

160
00:09:33.869 --> 00:09:34.140
that

161
00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:39.340
some of these carriers should be screened without a family history of pancreas

162
00:09:39.420 --> 00:09:42.300
cancer. ASGE suggests screening

163
00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:46.320
BRCA1 and BRCA2 carriers at

164
00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:50.030
age 50 without a family history. And in the NCCN now, it is

165
00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:53.620
standard of care to do screening of ATM and BRCA

166
00:09:53.680 --> 00:09:57.440
carriers at age 50. And that's because if you, in particular, take

167
00:09:57.480 --> 00:10:01.400
ATM and BRCA2 carriers, the lifetime risk of getting pancreas cancer is

168
00:10:01.420 --> 00:10:05.180
going to be about 5% to 7%. And when you're talking for a lethal

169
00:10:05.260 --> 00:10:07.800
cancer, it would make sense to do screening.

170
00:10:07.860 --> 00:10:11.790
Importantly, also, when we started to implement doing germline testing for

171
00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:15.680
all pancreatic cancer patients in the United States, and we

172
00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:19.520
found that individuals had a mutation, and we asked them, "Do

173
00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:23.720
you have a history of pancreas cancer in the

174
00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:27.160
family?" Over 80% of the time, the answer was no.

175
00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:31.140
So that let us know that we don't want to solely rely on family

176
00:10:31.220 --> 00:10:33.620
history to understand who's at risk.

177
00:10:34.380 --> 00:10:36.320
Other important cohorts here

178
00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:41.380
are cohort three. So these are people who should be screened, but they're

179
00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:45.409
too young. So if we had a prevention approach

180
00:10:45.820 --> 00:10:49.360
for individuals at high risk of pancreas cancer, this is a cohort that may come

181
00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:53.340
into play. Cohort four, and this is important to know if you have a single

182
00:10:53.480 --> 00:10:57.280
first-degree family member with pancreas cancer, it's now in the NCCN

183
00:10:57.289 --> 00:10:59.470
guidelines that you should get germline testing.

184
00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:04.200
And we currently have about 1,300 patients in cohort four in

185
00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:04.860
this study.

186
00:11:07.020 --> 00:11:10.990
Cohort five is just to be able to collect a biosample from a

187
00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:13.840
family where we may be able to do some important research.

188
00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:16.300
Cohort 6A is

189
00:11:17.540 --> 00:11:21.160
the strength of the study. We predict that about 1,200

190
00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:24.300
people who are in screening will get pancreas cancer

191
00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:28.170
during their participation. And the good

192
00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:31.960
