00:28:55.380 --> 00:28:59.260
esophagus and its cancer progression, a work that our team

497
00:28:59.320 --> 00:29:01.969
in Cleveland has been engaged in for some years now.

498
00:29:04.420 --> 00:29:07.990
More succinctly, I'm going to talk about biomarker-based interception of

499
00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:09.940
esophageal adenocarcinoma.

500
00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:13.800
These are my disclosures.

501
00:29:16.120 --> 00:29:19.960
And this is the challenge of esophageal adenocarcinoma,

502
00:29:20.110 --> 00:29:20.780
or EAC.

503
00:29:21.640 --> 00:29:25.600
It's been the fastest growing solid tumor in the United States

504
00:29:25.660 --> 00:29:29.040
over the last several decades. It has a five-year

505
00:29:29.200 --> 00:29:32.740
survival of less than 20%, a death toll that now

506
00:29:32.780 --> 00:29:36.620
exceeds that of ovarian cancer, and it is seldom, seldom

507
00:29:36.660 --> 00:29:37.600
detected early.

508
00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:44.710
Now, the opportunity to intercept this disease lies in the

509
00:29:44.740 --> 00:29:48.680
fact that it has an obligate precursor, which is known

510
00:29:48.720 --> 00:29:52.560
as Barrett's esophagus. And here on

511
00:29:52.600 --> 00:29:55.920
the slide, you can see the transition from the normal squamous

512
00:29:55.980 --> 00:29:58.870
histology of the esophagus to this columnar

513
00:29:58.900 --> 00:30:02.560
histology that marks the Barrett's condition and that gives

514
00:30:02.660 --> 00:30:05.360
rise to the esophageal adenocarcinomas.

515
00:30:07.280 --> 00:30:11.040
Now, Barrett's is thought to be initiated by esophageal injury,

516
00:30:11.480 --> 00:30:15.320
most commonly longstanding gastroesophageal reflux disease

517
00:30:15.360 --> 00:30:15.940
or GERD.

518
00:30:18.460 --> 00:30:22.360
And the Barrett's itself has a progression phase to

519
00:30:22.380 --> 00:30:26.320
Barrett's with dysplasia, which are the immediate precursors of the cancers.

520
00:30:27.620 --> 00:30:30.940
Now, the importance of this process is that if these

521
00:30:31.010 --> 00:30:34.590
dysplasias are detected, they can be ablated through

522
00:30:34.620 --> 00:30:38.520
endoscopic technologies, thereby intercepting and preventing the

523
00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:42.204
cancer.The

524
00:30:42.304 --> 00:30:45.704
other important thing about Barrett's is that it arises in a

525
00:30:45.824 --> 00:30:49.784
stereotypical location in the distal esophagus, right near the

526
00:30:49.804 --> 00:30:51.564
gastroesophageal junction.

527
00:30:52.584 --> 00:30:56.504
Okay? Now, because of the burden of this disease,

528
00:30:57.064 --> 00:31:00.784
the American College of Gastroenterology has recommended Barrett's

529
00:31:00.824 --> 00:31:04.774
screening for all men with chronic GERD and

530
00:31:04.804 --> 00:31:07.914
two additional risk factors from the list that's shown.

531
00:31:10.424 --> 00:31:10.984
However,

532
00:31:11.964 --> 00:31:15.444
endoscopic screening for Barrett's has been a massive failure in

533
00:31:15.524 --> 00:31:18.724
acceptance, both by patients and by physicians.

534
00:31:19.264 --> 00:31:23.124
And the result is that 95% of the time when an esophageal

535
00:31:23.164 --> 00:31:27.064
adenocarcinoma is diagnosed, there was never any screening

536
00:31:27.104 --> 00:31:29.544
to detect the antecedent Barrett's condition.

537
00:31:32.644 --> 00:31:36.264
So to attempt to do something about this, our

538
00:31:36.304 --> 00:31:39.684
group decided to look for biomarkers that could

539
00:31:39.724 --> 00:31:43.264
be present in Barrett's and esophageal cancers.

540
00:31:43.964 --> 00:31:47.044
And we initially focused on methylated DNAs.

541
00:31:47.844 --> 00:31:51.464
We did a genome-wide screen for differentially methylated loci

542
00:31:51.764 --> 00:31:55.524
that were diagnostic of Barrett's or esophageal adenocarcinomas,

543
00:31:56.304 --> 00:32:00.144
in part using reduced representation bisulfite sequencing

544
00:32:00.204 --> 00:32:02.104
from biopsies of these conditions.

545
00:32:03.464 --> 00:32:07.344
Now, that biopsy-based screen nominated two

546
00:32:08.364 --> 00:32:10.104
differentially methylated loci.

547
00:32:11.644 --> 00:32:13.764
The first of these was methylated vimentin.

548
00:32:14.254 --> 00:32:18.124
Now, this was a locus we had previously discovered as

549
00:32:19.224 --> 00:32:23.134
a wonderful biomarker of colon carcinomas, and

550
00:32:23.164 --> 00:32:26.644
indeed, we had brought this forward in collaboration with Exact

551
00:32:26.744 --> 00:32:30.524
Sciences as the Cologuard test, and it was the first methylated

552
00:32:30.544 --> 00:32:33.974
DNA stool test for early detection of colon cancer.

553
00:32:34.464 --> 00:32:38.344
We found it was even more commonly present in the Barrett's than it was in the

554
00:32:38.404 --> 00:32:41.784
colon. The second biomarker was methylated

555
00:32:41.824 --> 00:32:45.384
CCNA1 that came out of the reduced representation

556
00:32:45.424 --> 00:32:49.204
bisulfite screen. So to validate these biomarkers,

557
00:32:49.824 --> 00:32:53.624
we took advantage of a cohort of nearly 300 individuals

558
00:32:53.864 --> 00:32:57.784
who had had endoscopically guided cytology brushings, and we

559
00:32:57.864 --> 00:33:01.824
analyzed the DNA off of those cytology brushings and found that both

560
00:33:01.904 --> 00:33:05.724
methylated vimentin and methylated CCNA1 could

561
00:33:05.744 --> 00:33:09.584
distinguish the normal esophagus from the Barrett's esophagus with an

562
00:33:09.644 --> 00:33:13.634
AUC of over 0.95 for both of these markers

563
00:33:13.684 --> 00:33:14.364
individually.

564
00:33:15.524 --> 00:33:19.484
So that got us biomarkers. Of course, we still needed to find a way

565
00:33:19.504 --> 00:33:20.884
to get rid of the endoscope.

566
00:33:22.684 --> 00:33:26.644
And to do that, we developed a swallowable

567
00:33:26.784 --> 00:33:27.724
textured balloon,

568
00:33:28.724 --> 00:33:32.684
shown here in cartoon form, with the idea that it could be pulled back

569
00:33:32.764 --> 00:33:36.564
through the gastroesophageal junction to get what would effectively be a

570
00:33:36.624 --> 00:33:38.704
Pap smear of the distal esophagus.

571
00:33:39.724 --> 00:33:41.904
Now, this is what the device actually looks like.

572
00:33:43.804 --> 00:33:47.684
And here is the balloon tip, which is the functional part of the

573
00:33:47.744 --> 00:33:51.404
device. And if we hone in on it, what you can see

574
00:33:52.144 --> 00:33:55.704
is that the tip of the device is actually a capsule about the size of a

575
00:33:55.744 --> 00:33:58.244
vitamin pill. Here's the close-up.

576
00:33:58.904 --> 00:34:02.564
And in the stomach, one can insert air through this silicon

577
00:34:02.664 --> 00:34:06.644
catheter that's attached and pop out the textured balloon to

578
00:34:06.684 --> 00:34:10.444
get the best sample. Now importantly, once you have the

579
00:34:10.455 --> 00:34:14.245
sample, you can then withdraw the air and pop the balloon back

580
00:34:14.284 --> 00:34:18.044
inside the capsule, and this now traps the sample and

581
00:34:18.064 --> 00:34:21.944
protects it from dilution and contamination as you pull

582
00:34:21.984 --> 00:34:24.784
this back through the esophagus and the oropharynx.

583
00:34:26.404 --> 00:34:28.624
So here's how it looks from the patient point of view.

584
00:34:28.933 --> 00:34:30.745
The patient swallows the capsule.

585
00:34:31.404 --> 00:34:34.964
In the stomach, the air is inserted, and the balloon is deployed.

586
00:34:35.364 --> 00:34:37.304
You pull it back to get the Pap smear.

587
00:34:37.644 --> 00:34:40.984
You take the air out to invert the balloon and trap the sample.

588
00:34:41.384 --> 00:34:45.094
And then once it's out of the patient through the mouth, you can cut off the

589
00:34:45.144 --> 00:34:46.564
balloon and send it to the lab.

590
00:34:48.004 --> 00:34:51.424
So we combined the biomarker panel and the balloon

591
00:34:52.304 --> 00:34:56.284
and did an initial pilot trial of this technology, finding

592
00:34:56.324 --> 00:34:59.864
that we had 90% sensitivity for detecting

593
00:34:59.884 --> 00:35:03.824
non-dysplastic early-stage Barrett's esophagus, and that was

594
00:35:03.884 --> 00:35:06.004
at a 92% specificity.

595
00:35:07.684 --> 00:35:11.293
Now, since our initial "Science Translational Medicine" publication,

596
00:35:11.784 --> 00:35:14.674
there are now four clinical trials of this technology.

597
00:35:16.644 --> 00:35:20.254
Across these four cohorts, the sensitivity for detecting

598
00:35:20.324 --> 00:35:23.144
Barrett's has ranged between 80% and 90%.

599
00:35:24.424 --> 00:35:27.984
The sensitivity for detecting

600
00:35:28.104 --> 00:35:30.964
cancer has basically been 100%,

601
00:35:31.764 --> 00:35:33.564
with one anomalous case missed.

602
00:35:36.124 --> 00:35:39.924
And the specificity of the approach has also ranged

603
00:35:39.964 --> 00:35:41.784
between 80% and 90%.

604
00:35:42.944 --> 00:35:46.604
Of a clinical value, the positive predictive value of the

605
00:35:46.644 --> 00:35:50.184
technology is over 30%, and the negative predictive

606
00:35:50.264 --> 00:35:52.564
value is nearly 99%.

607
00:35:55.264 --> 00:35:59.064
So at this point, the status of the technology is that it has a

608
00:35:59.144 --> 00:36:01.524
name. The balloon is called EsaCheck.

609
00:36:01.784 --> 00:36:04.644
The methylated DNA panel is called EsaGuard.

610
00:36:05.404 --> 00:36:08.984
The EsaCheck device has been awarded 510approval from the

611
00:36:09.084 --> 00:36:12.744
FDA. The EsaGuard test panel has been awarded FDA

612
00:36:12.844 --> 00:36:14.564
breakthrough device designation.

613
00:36:15.444 --> 00:36:19.204
And the EsaCheck and EsaGuard test combination were

614
00:36:19.244 --> 00:36:23.234
included in the 2022 American College of Gastroenterology

615
00:36:23.604 --> 00:36:25.684
updated Barrett's clinical guidelines.

616
00:36:26.624 --> 00:36:30.544
The technology has now been successfully commercialized, and

617
00:36:30.584 --> 00:36:34.124
a Medicare CMS review is pending for insurance

618
00:36:34.244 --> 00:36:34.724
coverage.

619
00:36:37.284 --> 00:36:38.144
So what's next?

620
00:36:39.224 --> 00:36:42.464
Well, first of all, 40% of esophageal

621
00:36:42.504 --> 00:36:46.464
adenocarcinomas arise in individuals who never report

622
00:36:46.524 --> 00:36:47.484
having reflux

623
00:36:47.584 --> 00:36:51.464
symptoms.So how do

624
00:36:51.504 --> 00:36:53.984
we address this population of individuals?

625
00:36:55.964 --> 00:36:59.844
So we tried to develop a pilot study to use the

626
00:36:59.904 --> 00:37:03.464
EASE チ ェ ッ ク ESAGR technology to screen asymptomatic but

627
00:37:03.524 --> 00:37:07.494
high-risk individuals. Now, we defined high risk as

628
00:37:07.564 --> 00:37:11.114
any individual with three risk factors for having Barrett's,

629
00:37:11.664 --> 00:37:14.994
and that basically comes down to white men over 50,

630
00:37:15.204 --> 00:37:16.784
Caucasian males over 50.

631
00:37:18.924 --> 00:37:22.444
We've done an initial pilot study of 120 of these high-risk

632
00:37:22.504 --> 00:37:26.284
individuals. Thirty-four of them were test positive for the

633
00:37:26.324 --> 00:37:30.154
methylation markers. Twenty-seven of those individuals have come to

634
00:37:30.184 --> 00:37:33.984
endoscopy now, and nine of them had Barrett's, giving us a positive

635
00:37:34.024 --> 00:37:37.644
predictive value in this population of 33%.

636
00:37:37.684 --> 00:37:41.404
Basically exactly the same positive predictive value as we got in a

637
00:37:41.444 --> 00:37:45.364
symptomatic GERD population and bringing promise

638
00:37:45.384 --> 00:37:46.884
that this approach could be used.

639
00:37:49.264 --> 00:37:52.824
Let's see. There we go. Eighty-six individuals were test

640
00:37:52.884 --> 00:37:56.764
negative, and 22 of those have come to endoscopy, and all

641
00:37:56.824 --> 00:38:00.684
of them were negative for Barrett's, giving us right now a negative predictive

642
00:38:00.744 --> 00:38:04.004
value of 100% in this asymptomatic population.

643
00:38:05.884 --> 00:38:09.804
Moving forward, we now have a clinical trial, a validation trial

644
00:38:09.864 --> 00:38:13.624
underway. I'm supported by an NIH Division of Cancer

645
00:38:13.704 --> 00:38:17.524
Prevention R01, with the aim of accruing 800 of these

646
00:38:17.584 --> 00:38:21.524
asymptomatic high-risk subjects to validate this screening approach.

647
00:38:24.604 --> 00:38:28.044
Here is the team that has been driving this technology forward,

648
00:38:28.644 --> 00:38:32.244
Amitab Chak and Joe Willis, with whom I developed the device,

649
00:38:32.944 --> 00:38:36.384
Helen Wanova, who developed the biomarker panel in our

650
00:38:37.064 --> 00:38:40.774
laboratory, and particularly Amitab Chak, who's led all of the clinical

651
00:38:40.904 --> 00:38:44.364
trials of this technology in collaboration with his clinical

652
00:38:44.404 --> 00:38:46.484
collaborators in the BetterNet consortium.

653
00:38:50.924 --> 00:38:54.624
However, identifying individuals with Barrett's is only the first step,

654
00:38:55.344 --> 00:38:59.023
because in order to intercept the cancers, we have to

655
00:38:59.044 --> 00:39:02.924
identify when the Barrett's progresses to dysplasia and then send these

656
00:39:03.044 --> 00:39:06.564
patients to ablation. And the challenge of this

657
00:39:07.224 --> 00:39:10.504
is indicated on this survival plot from the

658
00:39:10.564 --> 00:39:13.984
AGCC staging criteria for esophageal

659
00:39:14.044 --> 00:39:17.804
adenocarcinoma. And what you'll note is that even stage

660
00:39:17.984 --> 00:39:20.404
one, early stage one esophageal

661
00:39:20.424 --> 00:39:22.214
adenocarcinomas have

662
00:39:23.064 --> 00:39:27.024
over 20% 10-year mortality rate. So

663
00:39:27.064 --> 00:39:30.884
you really have to catch this disease at the stage of

664
00:39:30.964 --> 00:39:32.064
high-grade dysplasia

665
00:39:33.024 --> 00:39:36.824
or early intramucosal cancers, because once the disease is

666
00:39:36.884 --> 00:39:40.564
submucosal, even if it's stage one, there's a good chance these patients will

667
00:39:40.624 --> 00:39:41.084
succumb.

668
00:39:43.184 --> 00:39:45.024
So the standard approach has been

669
00:39:46.044 --> 00:39:49.724
triennial surveillance endoscopies and random

670
00:39:49.744 --> 00:39:53.304
biopsies. And the problem with that approach is that these small

671
00:39:53.404 --> 00:39:57.384
progressed clones of cancer and dysplasia are often missed by

672
00:39:57.464 --> 00:39:58.984
random biopsy sampling.

673
00:39:59.864 --> 00:40:03.724
Moreover, the esophageal adenocarcinomas can develop quickly,

674
00:40:04.224 --> 00:40:07.464
and they often present clinically in between these three-year

675
00:40:08.184 --> 00:40:12.124
interval surveillance exams. And even when they're caught

676
00:40:12.184 --> 00:40:15.744
under surveillance, 40% of these cancers are already

677
00:40:15.824 --> 00:40:16.564
metastatic.

678
00:40:17.364 --> 00:40:20.524
So we clearly need more sensitive methods than just random

679
00:40:20.564 --> 00:40:24.354
biopsies to detect high-risk progression during

680
00:40:24.384 --> 00:40:26.174
surveillance of Barrett's patients.

681
00:40:27.104 --> 00:40:30.844
So the molecular challenge here is finding a small progressed

682
00:40:30.854 --> 00:40:34.004
dysplastic Barrett's clone in a much larger

683
00:40:34.124 --> 00:40:36.344
non-dysplastic Barrett's segment.

684
00:40:36.384 --> 00:40:39.224
So this is the classic needle in the haystack problem.

685
00:40:40.944 --> 00:40:44.404
And this problem is amplified by the fact that blood doesn't help.

686
00:40:45.124 --> 00:40:48.964
And that's because these small clones of

687
00:40:48.984 --> 00:40:52.724
dysplastic Barrett's or of early stage one

688
00:40:52.964 --> 00:40:56.124
esophageal adenocarcinomas do not put enough

689
00:40:56.184 --> 00:40:59.664
ctDNA into the blood to be

690
00:40:59.684 --> 00:41:03.364
detected by any of the current ctDNA-based tests.

691
00:41:04.704 --> 00:41:05.184
However,

692
00:41:06.064 --> 00:41:07.264
the breakthrough was

693
00:41:08.184 --> 00:41:08.403
when

694
00:41:09.324 --> 00:41:13.124
our group, together with Bert Vogelstein's group, realized that we

695
00:41:13.184 --> 00:41:16.644
could take the technology that the Vogelstein lab had

696
00:41:16.684 --> 00:41:20.564
developed to detect ctDNA

697
00:41:20.604 --> 00:41:24.404
abnormalities in blood and instead apply it to a Barrett's

698
00:41:24.564 --> 00:41:26.524
brushing sample. All right.

699
00:41:27.464 --> 00:41:31.394
So the idea was to take a brushing of the esophagus of the

700
00:41:31.484 --> 00:41:32.564
patient with Barrett's,

701
00:41:33.784 --> 00:41:37.084
amplify that DNA on the brush with a

702
00:41:37.104 --> 00:41:40.774
PCR-based technology that would look at 350,000

703
00:41:40.844 --> 00:41:44.824
amplicons, sequence the amplicons, and then use

704
00:41:44.884 --> 00:41:48.444
read imbalances, too many reads or too few reads,

705
00:41:48.844 --> 00:41:52.084
as indicators of chromosomal gains or losses.

706
00:41:52.504 --> 00:41:56.424
Okay. And then we interrogated this panel of chromosomal

707
00:41:56.524 --> 00:41:59.844
gains or losses with an algorithm that we called Barrett's

708
00:41:59.964 --> 00:42:03.064
Aneuploidy Detection, or BAD. Okay.

709
00:42:04.424 --> 00:42:05.244
So let me show you.

710
00:42:06.604 --> 00:42:10.384
So the first question was, well, can you just use aneuploidy to detect Barrett's

711
00:42:10.404 --> 00:42:14.364
progression? And it is indeed true that high-grade

712
00:42:14.424 --> 00:42:17.984
dysplasias are highly aneuploid, as you see on this violin

713
00:42:18.064 --> 00:42:18.444
plot.

714
00:42:20.044 --> 00:42:23.944
The problem is that a third of non-dysplastic Barrett's are aneuploid

715
00:42:24.024 --> 00:42:27.764
as well. So aneuploidy alone is not a useful

716
00:42:27.804 --> 00:42:28.484
biomarker.

717
00:42:31.424 --> 00:42:31.784
Whoops.

718
00:42:33.524 --> 00:42:34.244
What happened there?

719
00:42:44.244 --> 00:42:45.204
Let's try this guy.

720
00:42:50.104 --> 00:42:55.552
Okay.So

721
00:42:55.612 --> 00:42:58.812
the breakthrough came from realizing that esophageal

722
00:42:58.872 --> 00:43:02.642
adenocarcinomas were typified by a stereotypical

723
00:43:02.732 --> 00:43:06.512
set of chromosomal gains or losses, as shown in this panel.

724
00:43:07.252 --> 00:43:10.991
And moreover, all the variability of this panel of gains or

725
00:43:11.072 --> 00:43:14.652
losses could be captured in just six of these

726
00:43:14.752 --> 00:43:17.972
chromosomal alterations, the ones that are shown in red.

727
00:43:20.672 --> 00:43:24.272
So here's a list of these six indicator chromosomal

728
00:43:24.392 --> 00:43:27.992
changes. And those of you who are cancer geneticists will

729
00:43:28.032 --> 00:43:31.992
immediately recognize that this maps very nicely into

730
00:43:32.232 --> 00:43:35.132
CDKN2A, P53,

731
00:43:35.972 --> 00:43:36.792
KRAS.

732
00:43:41.272 --> 00:43:45.112
And so these chromosomal gains and losses that we pulled

733
00:43:45.192 --> 00:43:48.881
out because they captured the variability of the panel, actually are

734
00:43:48.912 --> 00:43:52.032
driver events in the development of this malignancy.

735
00:43:53.092 --> 00:43:56.872
So here was the algorithm. We would take the BAD

736
00:43:57.032 --> 00:44:00.852
score, and we would ask, "Does a particular patient's lesion

737
00:44:00.912 --> 00:44:04.572
show aneuploidy?" And if it didn't, we set it aside.

738
00:44:04.712 --> 00:44:05.842
We called it Not Bad.

739
00:44:06.772 --> 00:44:10.572
If it did show aneuploidy, we then went further and asked,

740
00:44:10.722 --> 00:44:14.432
"Does the aneuploidy include gains or losses on our

741
00:44:14.472 --> 00:44:18.272
driver chromosome panel?" If it didn't, we again set the

742
00:44:18.312 --> 00:44:21.152
lesion aside. Initially, we called it Maybe Bad.

743
00:44:22.812 --> 00:44:26.712
But if a lesion showed both aneuploidy and a hit on a driver

744
00:44:26.752 --> 00:44:29.092
chromosome, we called it Very Bad.

745
00:44:31.332 --> 00:44:32.812
So here is a heat map,

